<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12146f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12146f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12146f"> 146(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ laychief &amp; abbot</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Si on ne peut dire quelle consid&eacute;ration jouissaient les premiers &eacute;v&ecirc;ques sans si&egrave;ges, l&apos;influence et l&apos;autorit&eacute; des &eacute;v&ecirc;ques s&eacute;culiers paraissent, d&egrave;s l&apos;origine, indiscut&eacute;es et conside&eacute;rables. Ils sont regard&eacute;s comme les &eacute;gaux des rois. Le recueil des lois, &laquo;le Senchus Mor&raquo;, consacre cette situation pr&eacute;pond&eacute;rante et en est le t&eacute;moin irr&eacute;cusable: Un roi injuste et un &eacute;v&ecirc;que infid&egrave;le sont plac&eacute;s sur le m&ecirc;me plan <br><font color="green">[127: If we cannot say exactly what consideration was enjoyed by the first bishops without sees, the influence and authority of the secular bishops appears from the very first to be indisputable. They were regarded as the equals of kings. The code of laws, the &ldquo;Senchus Mor,&rdquo; established this preponderant situation, and bears undeniable testimony to it. <mark>An unjust king and an unfaithful bishop are placed on the same footing</mark>]</font> <small> Riguet, Abb&eacute; <a name="RTSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RTSP"><cite title="source">Saint Patrice</cite></a> (1911) 151</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12150i" href="c12all.htm#c12150i">VI.C.12:150(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
